As arrayAs linked list \[ \begin{align} \text{elements} = [1, \ 2, \ 3, \ 4, &amp; \ 0, \ 0] \\ &amp; \uparrow \\ &amp; \text{top} \end{align} \] <pre><code>package com.example.stack

class ArrayStack &lt;T&gt; {

  @Suppress("UNCHECKED_CAST")
  private var elements: Array&lt;T?&gt; = arrayOfNulls&lt;Any?&gt;(8) as Array&lt;T?&gt;

  private var top = 0

  fun push(e: T) {
    maybeResize()
    elements[top++] = e
  }

  fun peek(): T? = if (top == 0) null else elements[top-1]

  fun pop(): T? {
    if (top == 0) return null
    return elements[--top].also {
      elements[top] = null
    }
  }

  fun size() = top

  fun isEmpty() = top == 0

  private fun maybeResize() {
    if (top &lt; elements.size) return
    elements = elements.copyOf(elements.size * 2)
  }
}
</code></pre> <p>why <code>Array&lt;T?&gt;</code> and not <code>Array&lt;T&gt;</code>?</p> <p>When we create an array of size <code>8</code>, all those <code>8</code> slots have to hold something. Since no elements have been pushed, they must hold <code>null</code>. </p> <p>Additionally, for primitive types we could be contend with <code>Array&lt;T&gt;</code>. But if we were to hold objects into it, allowing <code>null</code> helps prevent memory leaks.</p> <p>why <code>arrayOfNulls&lt;Any?&gt;</code>?</p> <p>When creating an array, JVM needs to allocate a contiguous block of memory, which requires knowing the size of <code>T</code> objects going in. Because of type erasure, JVM doesn't know what <code>T</code> is. So we tell it to create an array of <code>Any?</code>. </p> <p>The cast <code>as Array&lt;T?&gt;</code> is needed so we can assign it to the variable. Promising the compiler that we will treat it strictly as an array of <code>T?</code>.</p> <p>The suppression is needed because otherwise the kotlin complier will flag casting <code>Any?</code> to <code>T?</code>.</p> <pre><code>package com.example.stack

class ListStack&lt;T&gt; {
  private var head: Node&lt;T&gt;? = null
  private var size = 0

  fun push(e: T) {
    head = Node(e, head) // (1)
    size++
  }

  fun peek(): T? = head?.data

  fun pop(): T? {
    val curr = head ?: return null
    return curr.data.also { // (2)
      head = curr.next
      size--
    }
  }

  fun size() = size

  fun isEmpty() = head == null
}

private data class Node&lt;T&gt;(
  val data: T,
  var next: Node&lt;T&gt;? = null,
)
</code></pre> <ol> <li>When stack is empty, it's <code>head = Node(e, null)</code>. </li> <li>essentially move <code>head</code> forward <code>head = head.next</code>.</li> </ol> Unit tests <pre><code>package com.example.stack

import org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThat
import kotlin.test.BeforeTest
import kotlin.test.Test

class ArrayStackTest {

  private lateinit var stack: ArrayStack&lt;Int&gt;

  @BeforeTest
  fun setup() {
    stack = ArrayStack()
  }

  @Test
  fun empty() {
    assertThat(stack.isEmpty()).isTrue
    assertThat(stack.size()).isEqualTo(0)
    assertThat(stack.peek()).isNull()
    assertThat(stack.pop()).isNull()
  }

  @Test
  fun single() {
    stack.push(1)

    assertThat(stack.isEmpty()).isFalse
    assertThat(stack.size()).isEqualTo(1)
    assertThat(stack.peek()).isEqualTo(1)
    assertThat(stack.pop()).isEqualTo(1)

    assertThat(stack.isEmpty()).isTrue
    assertThat(stack.size()).isEqualTo(0)
    assertThat(stack.peek()).isNull()
    assertThat(stack.pop()).isNull()
  }

  @Test
  fun three() {
    stack.push(1)
    stack.push(2)
    stack.push(3)

    assertThat(stack.isEmpty()).isFalse
    assertThat(stack.size()).isEqualTo(3)

    assertThat(stack.peek()).isEqualTo(3)
    assertThat(stack.pop()).isEqualTo(3)

    assertThat(stack.peek()).isEqualTo(2)
    assertThat(stack.pop()).isEqualTo(2)

    assertThat(stack.peek()).isEqualTo(1)
    assertThat(stack.pop()).isEqualTo(1)


    assertThat(stack.isEmpty()).isTrue
    assertThat(stack.size()).isEqualTo(0)
    assertThat(stack.peek()).isNull()
    assertThat(stack.pop()).isNull()
  }

  @Test
  fun exceedsInitialCapacity_resizesCorrectly() {
    // Push 10 elements to force the underlying array of size 8 to resize
    for (i in 1..10) {
      stack.push(i)
    }

    assertThat(stack.isEmpty()).isFalse
    assertThat(stack.size()).isEqualTo(10)
    assertThat(stack.peek()).isEqualTo(10)

    // Pop everything to ensure the copied array maintained the exact LIFO order
    for (i in 10 downTo 1) {
      assertThat(stack.pop()).isEqualTo(i)
    }

    // Ensure the top pointer successfully walked all the way back to 0
    assertThat(stack.isEmpty()).isTrue
  }

}
</code></pre>

First approach <pre><code>fun isValid(s: String): Boolean {
  val stack = java.util.ArrayDeque&lt;Char&gt;()
  for (c in s) {
    when(c) {
      '(', '{', '[' -&gt; stack.push(c)
      else -&gt; {
        if (stack.isEmpty()) return false
        if (stack.pop() != c.opener) return false
      }
    }
  }
  return stack.isEmpty()
}

private val Char.opener: Char
  get() = when(this) {
    ')' -&gt; '('
    '}' -&gt; '{'
    ']' -&gt; '['
    else -&gt; '\n'
  }
</code></pre>

First approach <p>\(O(1)\) <code>push</code> and \(O(n)\) <code>pop</code></p> <p>We maintain two stacks. <code>enqueue</code> is straighforward, we simply always <code>push</code> to the first stack.</p> \[ \begin{align} \text{stack} = (] \ \ &amp; \ \ \text{aux} = (] \\ \text{enqueue}(1): \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \text{stack} = (1] \ \ &amp; \ \ \text{aux} = (] \\ \text{enqueue}(2): \ \ \ \ \ \ \text{stack} = (1, 2] \ \ &amp; \ \ \text{aux} = (] \\ \text{enqueue}(3): \ \ \text{stack} = (1, 2, 3] \ \ &amp; \ \ \text{aux} = (] \\ \end{align} \] <p><code>pop</code> is tricky. We move all elements from \(\text{stack} \rightarrow \text{aux}\). <code>aux.pop()</code> is our element in question. Finally we close with moving back elements from \(\text{aux} \rightarrow \text{stack}\).</p> \[ \begin{align} \text{dequeue}(): \ \ \ \ \text{stack} = (1, 2, 3] \ \ &amp; \ \ \text{aux} = (] \\ \text{stack} = (] \ \ &amp; \ \ \text{aux} = (\fbox{3}, 2, 1] \\ \text{stack} = (] \ \ &amp; \ \ \text{aux} = (2, 1] \\ \text{stack} = (1, 2] \ \ &amp; \ \ \text{aux} = (] \end{align} \] <p>here we pop \(3\) from \(\text{aux}\).</p> <pre><code>class MyQueue() {

  val stack = java.util.ArrayDeque&lt;Int&gt;()
  val aux = java.util.ArrayDeque&lt;Int&gt;()

  fun push(x: Int) {
    stack.push(x)
  }

  fun pop(): Int {
    stack to aux
    val result = aux.pop()
    aux to stack
    return result
  }

  fun peek(): Int {
    stack to aux
    val result = aux.peek()
    aux to stack
    return result
  }

  fun empty(): Boolean = stack.isEmpty()
}

// define our own `to` function.
infix fun &lt;T&gt; java.util.ArrayDeque&lt;T&gt;.to(dest: java.util.ArrayDeque&lt;T&gt;) {
  while (this.isNotEmpty()) {
    dest.push(this.pop())
  }
}
</code></pre> Second approach <p>Previous approach is pretty wasteful. If have a bunch of <code>pop</code> one after another, we are shifting elements back and forth between \(\text{stack} \leftrightarrow \text{aux}\).</p> <p>Approach here is to:</p> <ul> <li>always <code>push</code> to \(\text{stack}\).</li> <li>and always <code>pop</code> from \(\text{aux}\).</li> </ul> operation \(\text{stack}\) \(\text{aux}\) Comment \((]\) \((]\) <code>enqueue(1)</code> \((1]\) \((]\) always <code>push</code> to \(\text{stack}\) <code>enqueue(2)</code> \((2, 1]\) \((]\) <code>enqueue(3)</code> \((3, 2, 1]\) \((]\) <code>dequeue()</code> \((]\) \((1, 2, 3]\)\((\fbox{1}, 2, 3]\)\((2, 3]\) since \(\text{aux}\) is empty, \(\text{stack} \rightarrow \text{aux}\)<code>pop</code> from \(\text{aux}\) <code>dequeue()</code> \((]\) \((\fbox{2},3]\)\((3]\) since \(\text{aux}\) is not empty simply <code>pop</code> from \(\text{aux}\) <pre><code>class MyQueue() {

  val stack = java.util.ArrayDeque&lt;Int&gt;()
  val aux = java.util.ArrayDeque&lt;Int&gt;()

  fun push(x: Int) {
    stack.push(x)
  }

  fun pop(): Int {
    if (aux.isEmpty()) {
      stack to aux
    }
    return aux.pop()
  }

  fun peek(): Int {
    if (aux.isEmpty()) {
      stack to aux
    }
    return aux.peek()
  }

  fun empty(): Boolean = stack.isEmpty() &amp;&amp; aux.isEmpty()
}

infix fun &lt;T&gt; java.util.ArrayDeque&lt;T&gt;.to(dest: java.util.ArrayDeque&lt;T&gt;) {
  while (this.isNotEmpty()) {
    dest.push(this.pop())
  }
}
</code></pre>

Expand <p>We use a single underlying queue \(q\).</p> <ul> <li><code>push</code> on <code>MyStack</code> translates to <code>q.enqueue</code>, followed by \(n-1\) <code>dequeue</code>-<code>enqueue</code>.</li> <li><code>pop</code> on <code>MyStack</code> translates to <code>q.dequeue</code> where we treat the front of \(q\) as the top of the stack.</li> </ul> \[ \begin{align} \text{stack} &amp;= (] \\ \text{push}(1) &amp;= (1] \\ \text{push}(2) &amp;= (1, 2] \rightarrow (2, 1] \\ \text{push}(3) &amp;= (2, 1, 3] \rightarrow (3, 2, 1] \\ \end{align} \] <p>where \((\) is the front of the queue.</p> <pre><code>class MyStack() {

  val queue = java.util.ArrayDeque&lt;Int&gt;()

  fun push(x: Int) {
    queue.add(x)
    repeat(queue.size - 1) {
      queue.add(queue.removeFirst())
    }
  }

  fun pop(): Int = queue.removeFirst()

  fun top(): Int = queue.first()

  fun empty(): Boolean = queue.isEmpty()
}
</code></pre>

MinStack.kt<pre><code>private var min = 0
private val stack = ArrayDeque&lt;Int&gt;()

fun min(): Int? {
  if (stack.isEmpty()) return null
  return min
}

fun peek(): Int? {
  if (stack.isEmpty()) return null
  if (stack.last() &lt; min) return min
  return stack.last()
}

fun push(e: Int) {
  if (stack.isEmpty()) {
    stack.addLast(e)
    min = e
  } else if (e &lt; min) {
    stack.addLast(2 * e - min)
    min = e
  } else {
    stack.addLast(e)
  }
}

fun pop(): Int? {
  if (stack.isEmpty()) return null
  if (stack.last() &lt; min) {
    return min.also {
      min = 2 * min - stack.removeLast()
    }
  }
  return stack.removeLast()
}
</code></pre> MaxStack.kt<pre><code>private var max = 0
private val stack = ArrayDeque&lt;Int&gt;()

fun max(): Int? {
  if (stack.isEmpty()) return null
  return max
}

fun peek(): Int? {
  if (stack.isEmpty()) return null
  if (stack.last() &gt; max) return max
  return stack.last()
}

fun push(e: Int) {
  if (stack.isEmpty()) {
    stack.addLast(e)
    max = e
  } else if (e &gt; max) {
    stack.addLast(2 * e - max)
    max = e
  } else {
    stack.addLast(e)
  }
}

fun pop(): Int? {
  if (stack.isEmpty()) return null
  if (stack.last() &gt; max) {
    return max.also {
      max = 2 * max - stack.removeLast()
    }
  }
  return stack.removeLast()
}
